        <p>For urgent situations, we can arrange courier collection of originals and express delivery of completed translations. Many clients send documents via WhatsApp while originals follow by courier, allowing translation to begin immediately.</p>
        
        <h3>Understanding Government Requirements</h3>
        <p>Dubai government authorities have specific requirements for translated documents. The Dubai Land Department requires MOJ-certified translations for all property registrations and transfers. Dubai Courts accept only properly certified translations with the translator's stamp and registration number clearly visible.</p>
        
        <p>The Department of Economic Development (DED) requires Arabic translations for licensing applications involving foreign documents. Dubai Health Authority (DHA) requires translated medical credentials for healthcare professional licensing. We understand these requirements and format translations appropriately.</p>
        
        <h3>Working With Dubai's International Community</h3>
        <p>Dubai's population comes from over 200 nationalities, speaking dozens of languages. While we primarily translate between Arabic and English—covering the vast majority of requirements—we can arrange translation from other languages when needed. Documents in French, German, Russian, Chinese, Hindi, Urdu, and other languages can be handled through qualified translators.</p>
        
        <p>Many Dubai residents maintain connections to their home countries, requiring documents to move in both directions. A birth certificate might need translation from Arabic for use abroad, while a foreign marriage certificate needs Arabic translation for UAE registration. We handle both directions with equal care.</p>
